Given a positive integer N, write a program to check whether it is a Neon Number.
A number is called a Neon Number if the sum of digits of its square is equal to the number itself.
Example:
9 → 9² = 81 → 8 + 1 = 9 → Neon number
1 → 1² = 1 → 1 = 1 → Neon number
10 → 10² = 100 → 1 + 0 + 0 = 1 → Not a neon number
Input Format

A single positive integer N
Constraints

0 ≤ N ≤ 10⁴
Output Format

Print true if the number is a Neon number, otherwise print false.
Sample Input 0

9
Sample Output 0

true
Sample Input 1

10
Sample Output 1

false

import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Solution {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);
        int n=sc.nextInt();
        int sq=n*n;
        int sum=0;
        while(sq!=0){
            sum+=sq%10;
            sq/=10;
        }
        if(sum==n){
            System.out.println("true");
        }else{
            System.out.println("false");
        }
    }
}
